{
  "text": "Of interest, past job analytic research has tended to focus on covariance-based measures [CITATION_1] , such as interrater reliability (DeNisi, [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , test-retest reliability [CITATION_4] , correlations between different response scales [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , and correlations between different data sources [CITATION_7] . The present study's use of the mean levels is valuable for three reasons. First, convergence in level ratings yields information distinctly different from that of covariance-based measures. In fact, the effects of self-presentation will be detected only by covariance-based measures if people self-present in different amounts (i.e., rank ordering changes). Level ratings thus provide a more sensitive measure to detect self-presentation. Second, as noted, many HR systems are developed through the use of frequency or importance ratings (i.e., level ratings are what are interpreted). If certain types of job analysis items are systematically under-or overestimated, this can affect the HR systems that result. Third, level ratings can be compared with each other instead of with some true score. This circumvents the problems associated with developing an absolute standard of accuracy.",
  "correct_citation": {
